A key trick for Rust/C++ polyglots: 
- In C++, `// \` continues the comment to the next line (backslash at end of line)
- In Rust, `// \` ends at the newline (backslash has no special meaning)

This means we can have code that is commented in C++ but visible in Rust, or vice versa!

For example:
```
// \
#include <stdio.h>
```
In C++: `// \` comments the next line too, so `#include <stdio.h>` is commented out.
In Rust: `// \` comments just the first line, `#include <stdio.h>` is visible (and would be an error).

But we want the opposite: C++ code visible in C++ but hidden in Rust.

